WEBVTT

1
00:00:02.160 --> 00:00:08.039
Hi, and welcome to another Designing Open Democracy podcast retrospective.

2
00:00:08.039 --> 00:00:16.540
This is an old recording that was held on the 21st of October 2017, as part of an event called Citizens' Democracy.

3
00:00:16.540 --> 00:00:31.240
We actually also released a previous podcast recording on this same event, on behalf of another speaker called Nicholas Gruen, who was talking about his own take on Citizens Juries and Deliberative Democracy.

4
00:00:31.240 --> 00:00:42.260
As like before, this event was sponsored by the York Butter Factory, a co-working space in Melbourne, as well as been hosted by Brian Koo and Nicholas Moran.

5
00:00:42.260 --> 00:00:49.060
The speaker today will be Hubertus Hofkirchner, who is the Austrian Chief Filters and CEO of Prediki.

6
00:00:49.060 --> 00:00:57.320
He also started a political party called Austrian GILT to try and push through his new system of Citizens Juries.

7
00:00:57.340 --> 00:01:11.860
And through this talk, you will learn about how Prediki was started, as well as this notion of a deliberative model and how technologies can be such a sentiment analysis can be used to help enhance such a model.

8
00:01:11.860 --> 00:01:24.200
What he will also talk about is how through allowing for specialization, what you allow is to increase the political bandwidth that Citizen Juries can provide to the political system.

9
00:01:24.200 --> 00:01:31.420
Just so you know, this audio was taken over a scout recording, so the audio may not be as good as it could be.

10
00:01:31.420 --> 00:01:36.800
However, hopefully you will be able to get the most important points across from his presentation.

11
00:01:36.800 --> 00:01:38.140
Enjoy the speech.

12
00:01:38.140 --> 00:01:42.440
We shall start with a quick background introduction by Hubertus Hofkirchner himself.

13
00:01:43.660 --> 00:01:50.100
So before I start with that story maybe shortly, why am I doing that?

14
00:01:50.100 --> 00:02:16.880
Just from my background, I used to be an investment banker in last millennium in the IT space, high tech space, and then founded the first online brokerage in Austria, which then expanded to southeastern Europe and which got overtaken later by an Austrian bank, and became then luckily the CEO of one of the Austrian telecom companies.

15
00:02:16.880 --> 00:02:28.420
Not the largest one, actually, the smallest of four, but still it was an interesting job because it was almost bankrupt when I had to take the job, so it was not easy.

16
00:02:28.420 --> 00:02:39.560
But the team and I, we effectively structured it with over some like three years, and in the end it got bought by Deutsche Telekom for about one and a half billion euros.

17
00:02:39.560 --> 00:02:45.360
So it was a nice deal, and I've been a serial entrepreneur ever since.

18
00:02:45.380 --> 00:02:56.880
One of the project which I'm currently called Prediki, effectively the idea of it originated in the time of when I was running the online broker because the world was truly mad at that moment.

19
00:02:57.940 --> 00:03:09.140
It was the time of the Internet bubble, and some of you may remember that the stock exchange valuations for some of these new Internet companies just went completely haywire.

20
00:03:11.620 --> 00:03:27.800
Little Internet companies which were co-founded by media companies, all of a sudden were worth more than media companies which had been around for dozens of years, and then had a huge market valuation.

21
00:03:28.860 --> 00:03:38.320
And I think what's important to know is, I at the time looked at some of these things and thought, okay, these valuations are completely crazy.

22
00:03:38.320 --> 00:03:48.980
And still, while knowing that, I found the trap of believing this general madness and acting according to it.

23
00:03:48.980 --> 00:03:55.620
So I made a couple of good investments, but I also made a couple of bad investments, where I had known that I shouldn't do that.

24
00:03:55.620 --> 00:04:08.740
And Nick mentioned before the problem of, in surveys, people sometimes say what they think before they think, and it's a big problem, which you can realize everywhere.

25
00:04:08.740 --> 00:04:15.680
We see it in the stock exchange, when there are hype-sites, we see it regularly before elections.

26
00:04:15.680 --> 00:04:16.860
I'm gonna talk about that.

27
00:04:16.959 --> 00:04:28.080
So we know how parties and the leadership acts to get our votes, that they do dirty campaigning, that they're lying, that they're making promises which they're never gonna keep.

28
00:04:28.080 --> 00:04:30.080
And still, people don't change.

29
00:04:30.080 --> 00:04:33.280
They vote for these people, they vote for these practices.

30
00:04:36.120 --> 00:05:01.600
And Prediki is a project which seems to be succeeding now to stop the collective maleness, to not produce a crowd which is mad, like Sigmund Freud would have us know, because Sigmund Freud, the Austrian psychologist, thought that crowds, once they cluster, they become stupid, irrational, violent.

31
00:05:02.200 --> 00:05:15.380
Whereas later, the Austrian School of Economics, of which Schumpeter, which Nick already mentioned, is one, thought that if you put them in proper processes, there's something evolving which we call collective intelligence.

32
00:05:15.380 --> 00:05:25.400
So the trick to make people think is to give them tools which don't produce madness, but which raise collective intelligence.

33
00:05:25.400 --> 00:05:36.800
And as Nick also explained already, that most of the tools, all of the tools which we have right now on the internet, Twitter, Facebook particularly, they do not do that.

34
00:05:36.800 --> 00:05:46.540
They rather help with mobbing, creating mobs, as you can see in this comment section.

35
00:05:46.540 --> 00:05:50.280
It's not designed to make people think.

36
00:05:50.280 --> 00:06:07.980
So that said, one of the spin-offs which we have from, I'm also part of the Hayek Institute, which is an institute which keeps up Austrian economics like the tradition of the more scientific economists like Schumpeter, Mises and Hayek.

37
00:06:07.980 --> 00:06:30.420
And about a year and a half ago, we did a spin-off called New Dermatology, which essentially thinks that we should not have party democracy anymore, because you have an agency problem in parties, which has been recognized 30 hundred years ago, actually, by somebody who called it the Iron Law of Oligarchy.

38
00:06:30.420 --> 00:06:46.360
Essentially meaning that if there's an organization, a party, in the end, after a little while, that party will serve not its original mission, but it will serve the people running it, which pretty much, I think, describes what parties do.

39
00:06:46.360 --> 00:06:53.200
And here in Europe, we already had a very bad experience after the discovery of this Iron Law of Oligarchy.

40
00:06:53.820 --> 00:06:55.180
That was in 1910.

41
00:06:55.180 --> 00:07:03.660
And by 1934, 1938, half of Europe had reacted according to this Law of Oligarchy.

42
00:07:03.660 --> 00:07:10.340
We had people like Hitler in, you heard about him already, there was Mussolini in Italy, there was Franco in spain.

43
00:07:10.340 --> 00:07:14.880
So this theory turned out to be a rather robust theory.

44
00:07:14.880 --> 00:07:23.840
And so to say, my fear is if it happens again, and these people will fall, ultimately, but while they fall, then now they're atom bombs at this position.

45
00:07:23.840 --> 00:07:30.320
So I'm not particularly looking forward to the next instance of the Law of Oligarchy striking.

46
00:07:30.320 --> 00:07:33.560
And we believe it will strike.

47
00:07:33.560 --> 00:07:42.000
Because, for instance, in Austria, you know, the same in, let me just share my screen with you for a moment.

48
00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:52.020
I don't know whether it's the same in Australia, but like Australia, Austria is one of the probably most wealth countries in the world.

49
00:07:52.020 --> 00:08:01.160
And still when we ask the people, sorry, this is in German, unfortunately, I'll translate it to you, how happy are the Austrians are gonna be with the next elected government?

50
00:08:01.160 --> 00:08:06.520
You could see that they were actually expecting to be quite dissatisfied.

51
00:08:07.920 --> 00:08:11.080
And still, everybody elected the same.

52
00:08:11.080 --> 00:08:28.640
And Prediki, which is this platform I built over the last couple of years, which fosters this thinking, effectively, they recognize that if we ask them in a normal poll, they think after the election, it's all gonna be better, which is really, really weird.

53
00:08:28.640 --> 00:08:32.980
So if you ask them, one year after the elections, do you think things will be better?

54
00:08:32.980 --> 00:08:34.720
The answer is here, green.

55
00:08:34.720 --> 00:08:38.340
Once you make them think, they say, no, it's not gonna be better.

56
00:08:38.340 --> 00:08:47.420
And with Prediki, we have a deliberative format where people essentially have to first bet what it's gonna be.

57
00:08:47.420 --> 00:09:01.160
So they don't just say it, they don't just tick a box, they have to bet, which is when the brain starts to switch into a different type of thinking, a slower type of thinking, but a more deliberative type of thinking.

58
00:09:01.160 --> 00:09:06.140
And we ask them after this bet, which they do, just show you this here.

59
00:09:06.140 --> 00:09:15.820
And so they have to essentially put little bets here with virtual currency, whether they think the Austrians are going to be a little more happy or more unhappy.

60
00:09:15.820 --> 00:09:23.960
And then once they've done that, they are prompted to put the reason to why this is being done so.

61
00:09:23.960 --> 00:09:36.320
And this is again something, going back to Siegmund Freud, once you've done something which is very simple and you need to justify it after what you start thinking, it's called post-rationalization.

62
00:09:36.320 --> 00:09:38.040
It's a very important principle.

63
00:09:38.560 --> 00:10:01.180
So whatever you did, your brain afterwards will tell you, okay, you did it intentional because of some fantastic reason, or if it went wrong, your brain will work out a reason why it should have been a fantastic thing, and just some silly idea prevented you a fantastic thought, fantastic immediate action to be true post-rationalization.

64
00:10:01.180 --> 00:10:23.740
Anyway, and what the system does with that, by the way, it then texts, so you can see down here how people argue more and more why they're going to be, so to say, dissatisfied, and you can see people write about the language comments on the system now, because it's able to do that and engages people in the conversation.

65
00:10:23.760 --> 00:10:31.420
One of the algorithms we wrote in the background then discloses this conversation into a sentiment analysis.

66
00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:50.800
So you can see down here in the rated comments that people mostly thought that we're rather dissatisfied, quite a few thought that we're very dissatisfied, and only very few people thought we would be satisfied, and then the system effectively dissects all the arguments in why this will be like that.

67
00:10:50.800 --> 00:11:00.360
You can see the overall reason why people thought they were dissatisfied after thinking about it, to say everything will remain as it was.

68
00:11:01.240 --> 00:11:04.420
As you can see, this is the very deep red bar.

69
00:11:04.420 --> 00:11:10.120
It caused a lot of dissatisfaction, and a lot of the others dissatisfied.

70
00:11:10.120 --> 00:11:13.240
And anything else, I think it didn't even matter so much.

71
00:11:13.240 --> 00:11:25.720
So it didn't matter that the Austrian administration is so slow, that the people are frustrated about the election choices, that the election promises are not being kept.

72
00:11:26.880 --> 00:11:33.580
The issue is, people are most dissatisfied that everything will remain the same.

73
00:11:33.580 --> 00:11:54.220
So we decided, in our Austrian Economics economist group, that we wanted to start an initiative, which we called New Demoky, which essentially tries to introduce, instead of the representative democracy system, which is iron law of oligarchy, which will result in the next atom war, I think, a system.

74
00:11:54.220 --> 00:12:03.060
And we were very aware that it couldn't just be any old democratic system, because we had observed, like Nick, the Brexit.

75
00:12:03.060 --> 00:12:15.760
And do you know, guys, after the day after the people in the UK decided that they wanted to exit the EU, Google announced the most frequent search of the day after.

76
00:12:15.760 --> 00:12:16.920
Do you know what it was?

77
00:12:16.920 --> 00:12:18.500
What is the EU?

78
00:12:19.940 --> 00:12:21.260
What is the EU?

79
00:12:21.260 --> 00:12:21.980
Exactly.

80
00:12:22.700 --> 00:12:31.500
The British people predominantly asked, what is the EU after the day that the majority voted to leave it?

81
00:12:31.500 --> 00:12:46.580
There was another example just at the time when we thought about it, which was the Greek referendum on the EU savings package, where the EU wanted austerity measures in Greece to essentially save the economy.

82
00:12:46.580 --> 00:12:51.060
The people, with 62 percent, voted against it.

83
00:12:51.060 --> 00:12:57.340
Two weeks later, Tsipras, the Prime Minister, simply went, yeah, okay, people are here, you voted against it.

84
00:12:57.340 --> 00:12:59.820
We changed this little by-sense, and now we're doing it.

85
00:12:59.820 --> 00:13:01.340
We agree.

86
00:13:01.340 --> 00:13:20.200
So the worst thing about this Greek referendum was actually that, and I was in Greece at the time, on a holiday when the ATM stopped working, actually just stopped working for me because I had demagnetized my card, but it was already switched off.

87
00:13:20.200 --> 00:13:33.600
Anyway, there were some interviews in the national television, and one of the ladies who was interviewed, Kari Kamevout, about this Greek, she said, should we do the saving package, should we not do it?

88
00:13:33.600 --> 00:13:37.400
In the open, the lady started to cry and said, I have no clue.

89
00:13:37.400 --> 00:13:39.200
I don't know what it means if I say yes.

90
00:13:39.200 --> 00:13:41.480
I don't know what will happen if I say no.

91
00:13:41.480 --> 00:13:48.440
So there's a certain amount of limited capacity to ask everybody.

92
00:13:48.440 --> 00:14:01.620
So we knew we needed something else, and we decided in the end that the best tool we could find so far was again Citizens Juries, like Nick already mentioned.

93
00:14:01.620 --> 00:14:21.580
However, we added to the recipe an open phase of surveying, of inquiry, which would give everybody the possibility to chip in there to sense, to say what they mean, but again in the deliverative format, which I've shown you before.

94
00:14:21.580 --> 00:14:22.840
So that was our recipe.

95
00:14:22.840 --> 00:14:26.680
And then we thought, okay, but how are we going to get people to participate?

96
00:14:26.820 --> 00:14:35.380
I guess the question is, and some of you may know that already, what is the biggest motivator for people to participate in democracy?

97
00:14:37.800 --> 00:14:39.480
In Australia, we make them.

98
00:14:41.720 --> 00:14:44.220
In Australia, we find them, if they don't, but...

99
00:14:44.220 --> 00:14:46.820
Yeah, you got it all, I know.

100
00:14:46.820 --> 00:14:47.820
No, but what...

101
00:14:47.820 --> 00:14:57.180
absence of force and violence, what's the best way to motivate people to participate in democracy?

102
00:15:01.140 --> 00:15:02.900
Someone said economic incentive.

103
00:15:04.080 --> 00:15:13.180
Well, I believe what they found out, that the overriding requirement is that what people say, what they decide, actually matters.

104
00:15:13.780 --> 00:15:17.880
Yeah, that these decisions are being implemented.

105
00:15:18.360 --> 00:15:20.260
That's the one big motivator.

106
00:15:20.260 --> 00:15:30.720
And ever since I knew about that, I've been observing all kinds of votes and things, and I'm just amazed how many never go to action and are being ignored.

107
00:15:31.300 --> 00:15:37.120
Because essentially, politicians think that people are too stupid to decide anything.

108
00:15:37.120 --> 00:15:42.580
If you ask the politician if people should get more say, the one answer we get is not that they're too stupid.

109
00:15:42.580 --> 00:15:43.240
They have no idea.

110
00:15:43.240 --> 00:15:45.560
They're all psychopaths still.

111
00:15:45.560 --> 00:15:47.600
Yeah.

112
00:15:47.600 --> 00:15:49.060
And we don't think it's true.

113
00:15:49.060 --> 00:16:00.240
And I think particularly in Australia, you guys have done a lot of experimentation, which is extremely well-documented, and there have been other things in Ireland and in the UK.

114
00:16:00.240 --> 00:16:03.300
And we've just done two in Austria.

115
00:16:03.300 --> 00:16:10.680
So we decided we need to implement it in such a way that whatever happens out of these Citizens Juries actually matter.

116
00:16:10.680 --> 00:16:21.140
So we started to look to working with the party to make them use the Citizens Juries, which we called B&#252;rgerparlament, so Citizen Parliaments.

117
00:16:21.480 --> 00:16:27.500
And it seemed that they would have liked that, because, okay, I mean, then they know what the people really want.

118
00:16:28.360 --> 00:16:34.860
They can put forward their program and know that the Austrians will be very happy doing what the Citizen Parliaments.

119
00:16:34.860 --> 00:16:43.840
But no, we approached three parties, and all of them declined to use that tool, partly because people are stupid.

120
00:16:44.680 --> 00:16:58.640
And I think, in reality, because the leading people there, they all have cushy, well-paying jobs, and they were kind of fearing that they would put themselves out of work, which frankly, I think they would.

121
00:16:58.640 --> 00:17:06.660
So it was a rational fear for them, who are the decision makers, but it's not a good solution for Austria.

122
00:17:06.660 --> 00:17:13.640
Luckily, I ran into a man called Roland D&#252;rner, who was just about to found their party.

123
00:17:13.740 --> 00:17:16.079
So he had not yet a position of power.

124
00:17:16.079 --> 00:17:20.780
And this was this guilt thing which Nick just mentioned.

125
00:17:20.780 --> 00:17:36.240
So far too late in July this year, no, it was June this year, we finally decided, okay, guilt is gonna adopt this model, which was the election that last Sunday, so which was three months ago.

126
00:17:36.240 --> 00:18:04.520
So we had three months to work out the idea to communicate it to the people, which was a bit of a problem, because Hubertus Hofkirchner was before I, running around more with the concept like Beppe Grillo in Italy, which means telling people, okay, this system is shit, just protest against it, put your vote here that you hate the system, La fanculo, let me have a wash, or kiss my back sides, that was the title of the party.

127
00:18:04.520 --> 00:18:12.640
So we had only three months to change that into something a little bit more productive, which I'm going to show you now, one second.

128
00:18:12.640 --> 00:18:20.060
So this is the concept which we, effectively, is happening today.

129
00:18:20.060 --> 00:18:51.680
So in general, you vote every five years, which gives you about 10 to 12 votes in your whole lifetime, and probably one or two months in front of each of these election dates where politicians care at least what you think is a mob, because all they do in the election campaigns is they're trying to emotionalize us with one nine-second sound bit, as Nick already said, and then they're in parliament, and then for five years, they effectively couldn't really care less of what you want.

130
00:18:51.680 --> 00:18:53.700
Of course, there's a lot of happening behind the scenes.

131
00:18:53.700 --> 00:19:07.340
So what we propose as the following is that essentially, everybody can participate in an open ideation phase of solutions, to exist to such solutions as the citizens come up with.

132
00:19:07.340 --> 00:19:27.060
And the key behind it is a kind of voting system, where every problem is rated, whether it's an important problem or not, not an important problem, whether a solution is a good solution, another solution, or whether an objection to a solution is a good objection or an irrelevant objection.

133
00:19:27.380 --> 00:19:50.560
And out of that, you can actually calculate an index, which will automatically, from all the thousands of ideas and problems which people report, always give you a couple which are on top because of the importance of the problems or the quality of the solution and the little objections which exist.

134
00:19:50.560 --> 00:20:12.500
There's a second open phase where then each of these proposal, proposed solution ideas is meeting an opening fire where everybody can participate, which will be part of a traditional questionnaire, which has a lot of problems as we know, but people are pretty good in responding to diagnostics.

135
00:20:12.500 --> 00:20:15.260
So if you ask four questions, are you a man, are you a woman?

136
00:20:15.260 --> 00:20:16.400
People typically know.

137
00:20:17.980 --> 00:20:25.560
But even if you ask, okay, what will the coin toss result in five minutes, there will be a huge bias.

138
00:20:25.560 --> 00:20:40.960
If asked now, and the survey people, Hubertus is tossing a coin, will it be heads or tails, or will it be tails or heads, to randomize it, you will get a response of 68 percent of people, that my coin toss will result in heads.

139
00:20:41.940 --> 00:20:44.320
Because of a very simple bias.

140
00:20:44.320 --> 00:20:51.600
So anybody following the survey would think that coins have three sides, and two of them are heads, which is of course rubbish.

141
00:20:51.600 --> 00:21:01.180
So we use it in a very limited way, and then for prognostics, we use the prediction market, which I just showed you, which is a much more deliberative format.

142
00:21:01.180 --> 00:21:23.080
Now the other problem we had to solve was this preconception, which not only politicians have, by the way, not only politicians think that the people are too stupid to decide, even people think that 90% of the other people are less competent in any area of topic than themselves.

143
00:21:23.080 --> 00:21:24.340
It's a huge issue.

144
00:21:24.340 --> 00:21:32.500
Of course, it can't be true, because intelligence and knowledge is normally distributed, it follows a nice Gauss curve, but it's a problem.

145
00:21:32.500 --> 00:21:44.440
Anyway, so we're using Prediki also to find out, so to say, who is knowledgeable in a topic or not.

146
00:21:44.440 --> 00:21:51.600
And we do that by effectively comparing the prediction of people with what actually happened.

147
00:21:51.600 --> 00:22:01.380
Because there's quite a lot of scientific evidence meanwhile, that people who are better in predicting what will happen, are actually also much better decision makers.

148
00:22:01.380 --> 00:22:09.280
There's a highly recommendable book issued in 2015 by a professor from the US called Philip Tetlock.

149
00:22:09.280 --> 00:22:11.620
It's called Super Forecasting.

150
00:22:11.620 --> 00:22:23.080
And it effectively shows how people who are tainted by ideology, by one big idea, get it all wrong when they have to say what will happen.

151
00:22:23.080 --> 00:22:30.220
Like me, maybe I'm getting it completely all wrong if I think that the world will be atom-bombed after the next round of dictators.

152
00:22:31.220 --> 00:22:32.340
Maybe even that will happen.

153
00:22:32.340 --> 00:22:37.940
Anyway, so if you are a socialist, you think you have to look at the world.

154
00:22:37.940 --> 00:22:44.000
If you are too much capitalist, you're generally wrong.

155
00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:49.660
Tetlock calls these guys hedgehogs because they just take a position and then they don't move.

156
00:22:49.660 --> 00:22:54.880
Whereas he calls the more intelligent people who are flexible, he calls them the foxes.

157
00:22:54.880 --> 00:22:56.820
So the fox knows many tricks.

158
00:22:56.820 --> 00:22:58.920
And these foxes also make better decisions.

159
00:22:59.620 --> 00:23:07.540
And the mechanism can actually rank people according to how good their predictions are.

160
00:23:07.540 --> 00:23:14.060
And if you're negative over a series, then we know most likely you're not such a good decision maker.

161
00:23:14.060 --> 00:23:18.440
So that's, where was I?

162
00:23:18.440 --> 00:23:22.080
Yeah, that's this principle of expert identification.

163
00:23:22.080 --> 00:23:24.700
And on the other hand, we don't want to restrict people.

164
00:23:24.700 --> 00:23:26.640
Everybody is good at something.

165
00:23:26.820 --> 00:23:29.660
It's like Andy Warhol's 15 Minutes of Fame.

166
00:23:29.660 --> 00:23:38.020
But each of us, while probably not being the best in anything, each of us is very good in one or two particular things.

167
00:23:38.020 --> 00:23:48.060
And which effectively means that we don't need to exclude even anybody from participating in the Citizens Juries, because there's no need to restrict the capacity.

168
00:23:48.060 --> 00:23:51.940
We can have hundreds and thousands of those things in parallel.

169
00:23:51.940 --> 00:24:01.320
And as long as we make sure that the right people go into the right parliament, where they will decide the right things, we could have an enormous bandwidth.

170
00:24:01.320 --> 00:24:03.720
Like in Austria, we have 8 million of us.

171
00:24:03.720 --> 00:24:10.860
So if only 1% of people participated, because everybody is busy, but 1%, that's 80,000 people.

172
00:24:10.860 --> 00:24:19.300
